comment_regular_data.body:
@nurupo I walked through testing with qTox with @cryptogospod at the time, the diff was adding the calls to the new API here: https://github.com/qTox/qTox/blob/da5c165f4116dce736def63b1b917523b848db09/src/core/toxoptions.cpp#L133.

The `QNetworkReply::ProxyAuthenticationRequiredError` was triggered from https://github.com/qTox/qTox/blob/da5c165f4116dce736def63b1b917523b848db09/src/net/updatecheck.cpp#L137 when qTox tries to check its release version over https, because it's loading its proxy info from settings, but not the proxy password which was just hacked in to toxoptions.

Agreed that the error doesn't say anything about toxcore, but I do think that @cryptogospod's testing showing that toxcore either connects or doesn't connect when using the proxy with the correct or incorrect password shows password support's working.

@nurupo what's the state of this? Can it be merged?

Mentioned in:
https://github.com/TokTok/c-toxcore/issues/1682#issuecomment-1925905581

The proxy works, as can be tested with microsocks and a modified echo_bot example, connecting to an online TCP relay node grabbed from https://nodes.tox.chat (or you could test it against a local DHT_bootstrap too).

First, in terminal 1:
```bash
$ apt install microsocks
$ microsocks -i 127.0.0.1 -p 1080 -u nurupo -P password
```

then, in terminal 2:
```bash
$ rm -rf ./_build ./prefix
$ cmake -B_build \
  -DENABLE_SHARED=ON \
  -DENABLE_STATIC=OFF \
  -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
  -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX="${PWD}/prefix"
$ cmake --build _build --parallel "$(nproc)" --target install
$ cat << 'EOF' > ./test.c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

#include <unistd.h>

#include <sodium/utils.h>
#include <tox/tox.h>

typedef struct DHT_node {
    const char *ip;
    uint16_t port;
    const char key_hex[TOX_PUBLIC_KEY_SIZE*2 + 1];
} DHT_node;

void self_connection_status_cb(Tox *tox, TOX_CONNECTION connection_status, void *user_data)
{
    switch (connection_status) {
        case TOX_CONNECTION_NONE:
            printf("Offline\n");
            break;
        case TOX_CONNECTION_TCP:
            printf("Online, using TCP\n");
            break;
        case TOX_CONNECTION_UDP:
            printf("Online, using UDP\n");
            break;
    }
}

int main()
{
    Tox_Options *options = tox_options_new(NULL);
    tox_options_set_udp_enabled(options, false);
    tox_options_set_local_discovery_enabled(options, false);
    tox_options_set_proxy_host(options, "127.0.0.1");
    tox_options_set_proxy_port(options, 1080);
    tox_options_set_proxy_type(options, TOX_PROXY_TYPE_SOCKS5);
    tox_options_set_proxy_socks5_username(options, "nurupo", strlen("nurupo"));
    tox_options_set_proxy_socks5_password(options, "hunter2", strlen("hunter2"));

    Tox *tox = tox_new(options, NULL);

    DHT_node nodes[] =
    {
        {"144.217.167.73", 33445, "7E5668E0EE09E19F320AD47902419331FFEE147BB3606769CFBE921A2A2FD34C"}
    };

    for (size_t i = 0; i < sizeof(nodes)/sizeof(DHT_node); i ++) {
        unsigned char key_bin[TOX_PUBLIC_KEY_SIZE];
        sodium_hex2bin(key_bin, sizeof(key_bin), nodes[i].key_hex, sizeof(nodes[i].key_hex)-1,
                       NULL, NULL, NULL);
        tox_bootstrap(tox, nodes[i].ip, nodes[i].port, key_bin, NULL);
        tox_add_tcp_relay(tox, nodes[i].ip, nodes[i].port, key_bin, NULL);
    }

    tox_callback_self_connection_status(tox, self_connection_status_cb);

    printf("Connecting...\n");

    while (1) {
        tox_iterate(tox, NULL);

        usleep(tox_iteration_interval(tox) * 1000);
    }

    tox_kill(tox);

    return 0;
}
EOF
$ gcc test.c -o test -std=gnu99 -lsodium \
  -I"$PWD/prefix/include/" -L"$PWD/prefix/lib/" -Wl,-rpath="$PWD/prefix/lib/" -ltoxcore
$ ./test
```

You should see in ternimal 1:

```bash
$ microsocks -i 127.0.0.1 -p 1080 -u nurupo -P hunter2
client[4] 127.0.0.1: connected to 144.217.167.73:33445
```

and in ternimal 2:

```bash
$ ./test
Connecting...
Online, using TCP
```

i.e. microsocks proxies the connection to the TCP relay node's address (which implies the auth was successful; microsocks doesn't print anything on a successful nor a failed auth), and the test program successfully connects via TCP.

@nurupo Thanks - I agree the simplest case covers corporate proxies which I feel is the target of this, and perhaps some Tor users.

What has to be done to get this merged? 2 failing, and 1 expected checks?
Does it need a review from someone?
